review_blob: Sampled at the Beach Club in Grand Cayman. Of fairly amateurish home brew standard. Infection evident. Wouldnt try it again unless nothing else was available on a hot day at the beach.
Very bland mainstream beer - appeals to the lowest common denominator. Cant see why its so popular. VB is better in my view.
Reddish colour, smooth finish. Decent quaffing beer - quite a bit better than the mainstream beers on offer in Australia, but nothing spectacular.

I had an impromptu beer tasting with my neighbour the other day. We consumed 12 bottles of beer, mainly top Belgian beers and a couple of Australian brews. The Coopers Vintage Ale (batch Oct 2002) remarkably hasd our unanimous vote as the clear second after the Belgian Bush Noel. The batch date is critical. The case of "best after August 2004" I recently bought will need to be cellared for at least another year before it starts hitting its straps.

Received a gift pack as a Christmas present. Disappointed by not living up to its marketing promise - particularly the brewerys great name. The brewers need to go back to the drawing board with a view to brewing a more flavoursome ale.

I still have quite a few bottles left of the first batch of the James Squire Strong Ale. The beer is only now hitting its straps (after 2 or 3 years). Due to its age a different beer from the ratings below. Malty aroma with strong coffee overtones.

A drinkable APA, but not in the league of Little Creatures Pale Ale, the best Australian beer in its category. Overpriced as a premium beer. Theres not much wrong with Crackenback APA, but it lacks aroma and zest.

Better and more bitter than VB and Tooheys New and therefore preferable to these two beers on tap. Reschs used to be the beer of choice in Sydney and the rest of NSW. A friend told me that in the sixties and seventies Reschs was available on 17 of the 20 taps at his local pub. The options were therefore Reschs or Reschs. Many oldtimers drink the beer out of habit.
Typical mass produced beer. Too chemical and hangover inducing. One for the plebs.
Cloudy bottled fermented ale. Bottled ale not as good as on tap. Lacks fruity flavours of quality ales such as Little Creatures Pale Ale, but otherwise not a bad beer.

beer_name: James Squire Jack of Spades Porter

review_blob: A rather bland, insipid beer, but not as bad as some of the other mass market Australian beers. Most of the flavour appears to have been leached out through the filtering process. Probably OK with a hot curry.

Exquisite floral and fruity flavors. Very drinkable. Thoroughly enjoyed the first bottle I had at Doyles in Watsons Bay (Sydney) and was very pleased to find a six-pack at my local bottle shop yesterday. The best Australian bottled beer in my honest opinion (I havent had the fortune of tasting Little Creatures on tap as its currently only available in Western Australia).
An uncomplicated and honest stout. Tastes a bit too much like treacle for my liking. Would be good for a coalminer after a hard days work underground.

I have many happy memories of drinking copious amounts of Castle Lager whilst watching cricket during my youth in South Africa. A good beer for quenching your thirst in the hot sun. As my palate has improved during the years, I now find Castle a bit bland and unimaginative.

A very bland beer, tastes like cardboard. I had the misfortune of visiting a friends holiday home during the Christmas break, where he only had Tooheys Extra Dry in the fridge. As hes not a beer drinker, he made an honest mistake by buying Extra Dry in anticipation of my visit.
